    {
      "id": "PopularPost161628",
      "post_content": "This guy here is the textbook example of a card being much, much better than it looks. It seems at first to be a pretty beefy creature but with a pretty horrible drawback. Why, you can't even keep it on the field unless you control three other creatures. Madness! In practice, however, this guy is much, much more.  \n  \nFirst, he can save your creatures. Saving three from Earthquake and then surviving is no mean feat. He can also save two and bounce himself, which nets you zero card disadvantage since the card you played just bought itself back to your hand.  \n  \nNext, enter- or leaves-the-battlefield effects. Bouncing the likes of [Bone Shredder](/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Bone Shredder) is a clearly great function of Dusty. But think bigger. Think evoke. Yes, you can play this in response to the evoke trigger, saving your evoker for another day, basically giving evokers Buyback ![2](/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&name=2&type=symbol)![White](/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&name=W&type=symbol)![White](/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&name=W&type=symbol). This is cool, but add Door of Destinies (tribal tiem!) or similar and this is one hell of an engine.  \n  \nA security blanket wrapped aro... [(see all)](javascript:void(0);)",
      "posted_by": "ClockworkSwordfish",
      "html": "<div class=\"post oddItem\" id=\"PopularPost161628\">\n<span class=\"postContent\" id=\"ctl00_ctl00_ctl00_MainContent_SubContent_SubContent_popularPosts_postsRepeater_ctl07_post\">This guy here is the textbook example of a card being much, much better than it looks. It seems at first to be a pretty beefy creature but with a pretty horrible drawback. Why, you can't even keep it on the field unless you control three other creatures. Madness! In practice, however, this guy is much, much more.<br/><br/>First, he can save your creatures. Saving three from Earthquake and then surviving is no mean feat. He can also save two and bounce himself, which nets you zero card disadvantage since the card you played just bought itself back to your hand.<br/><br/>Next, enter- or leaves-the-battlefield effects. Bouncing the likes of <a class=\"autoCard\" data:cardname=\"Bone Shredder\" href=\"/Pages/Card/Details.aspx?name=Bone Shredder\">Bone Shredder</a> is a clearly great function of Dusty. But think bigger. Think evoke. Yes, you can play this in response to the evoke trigger, saving your evoker for another day, basically giving evokers Buyback <img align=\"absbottom\" alt=\"2\" src=\"/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&amp;name=2&amp;type=symbol\"/><img align=\"absbottom\" alt=\"White\" src=\"/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&amp;name=W&amp;type=symbol\"/><img align=\"absbottom\" alt=\"White\" src=\"/Handlers/Image.ashx?size=small&amp;name=W&amp;type=symbol\"/>.  This is cool, but add Door of Destinies (tribal tiem!) or similar and this is one hell of an engine.<br/><br/>A security blanket wrapped aro... <a href=\"javascript:void(0);\" onclick=\"ExpandPost(event, this, 161628)\">(see all)</a></span>\n<div class=\"postDetails\" id=\"ctl00_ctl00_ctl00_MainContent_SubContent_SubContent_popularPosts_postsRepeater_ctl07_postDetails\" style=\"padding-top: 5px;\">\n<div class=\"reportAbuse\">\n<a href=\"http://wizards.custhelp.com/cgi-bin/wizards.cfg/php/enduser/ask.php?p_prods=5